photo.description: Teotihuacan is an enormous archaeological site in the Basin of Mexico, containing some of the largest pyramidal structures built in the pre-Columbian Americas. Apart from the pyramidal structures, Teotihuacan is also known for its large residential complexes, the Avenue of the Dead, and numerous colorful, well-preserved murals.

photo.description: This is me and Kim at the northwest corner of the Pyramid of the Sun. Surprisingly this corner wasn't much occupied even though it probably gives one of the better views of the complex. At the top, we met a friendly Italian who offered to take our photo for us if we would do the same for him.

photo.description: Below the pyramid is a nice view of this area with several platforms. Columns are splattered throughout the area, and it's hard to understand whether this area is semi-subterranean or if deposition has accumulated this much over time. I've interpreted this area as a marketplace under the pyramid.

photo.description: Looking down the slope of the Pyramid of the Sun is the small platform that splits the stairway from running down the middle of the pyramid's face to diverging either to the north or south. Beyond the platform is the Plaza of the Sun with the Sun Complex at its center. The market is to the north (right) with the "Sunset" complex to the south (left).
